<button class="accordion">What is conflict?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Conflict is a natural feature of human communication. We often see conflict as unfavourable, and it is true. A conflict that is not handled well can have a devastating impact on staff morale and productivity, as well as customer relations. However, when conflict is managed well, it can lead to increased creativity and enthusiasm among workers.</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What do you mean by conflict management?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Conflict management is the practice of recognising and dealing with disputes in a rational, balanced and effective way. Also, incorporating proper conflict management within a business environment encourages effective communication and excellent negotiation and problem-solving skills to restore the focus to the company's overall goals.<a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/search?q=conflict+management&type=productpos=1&_sid=c2dcef16d&_ss=rtarget="_blank""><font color="green"><u> Click here for online conflict management courses and training.</u></font></a></p><p></p><p></p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the types of conflict?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Generally, conflict is prevalent in the workplace setting. The three types of conflict that are common in organisations are task conflict, relationship conflict and value conflict. 
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the five styles for conflict management?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>As identified by Thomas and Kilmann, the five styles for conflict management are competing, compromising, collaborating, avoiding and accommodating. 
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What are the common conflict situations?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Common conflict situations include harassment issues, consistent lateness, social bullying, inappropriate humour in the workplace, aggressive behaviour and poor performance issues.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">What is the difference between conflict resolution and conflict management?</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Conflict management and conflict resolution are often used synonymously. On the one hand, managing conflict implies that the conflict exists. However, it is controlled in such a way that the conflict is not a significant problem. On the other hand, resolving conflict means that some end or solution to the conflict has been determined.
</p>
</div>
<button class="accordion">Why is conflict management training essential?
</button>
<div class="panel">
<p>Conflict management training aims to introduce practical conflict resolution techniques and strategies that managers and team leaders can effectively utilise when managing conflict in the workplace. It should build on previous training, skills and knowledge of effective performance management.
</p>
